post_cb({"8508299": {"ParentId": "8508266", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "6", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8508266_8508299_0\"><code>[C++11: 8.3.3/3]:</code> A pointer to member shall not point to a static\n  member of a class (9.4), a member with reference type, or \u201c<em>cv</em> void.\u201d [\n  <em>Note:</em> See also 5.3 and 5.5. The type \u201cpointer to member\u201d is distinct\n  from the type \u201cpointer\u201d, that is, a pointer to member is declared only\n  by the pointer to member declarator syntax, and never by the pointer\n  declarator syntax. <strong>There is no \u201creference-to-member\u201d type in C++.</strong> <em>\u2014end\n  note</em> ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "560648", "CommunityOwnedDate": "2011-12-14T16:48:40.253", "Id": "8508299", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T16:48:40.253", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T16:48:40.253"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8508266_8508299_0": {"section_id": 3227, "quality": 0.8421052631578947, "length": 32}}, "n3337": {"so_8508266_8508299_0": {"section_id": 3100, "quality": 0.8421052631578947, "length": 32}}, "n4659": {"so_8508266_8508299_0": {"section_id": 3984, "quality": 0.8157894736842105, "length": 31}}}, "8508266": {"CommentCount": "10", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8508299", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T16:46:23.810", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T17:04:22.537", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T10:30:08.527", "ViewCount": "590", "FavoriteCount": "2", "Title": "Does C++ support member function references?", "Id": "8508266", "Score": "8", "Body": "<p>C++ permits <em>function pointers</em> and <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/480248/function-references\"><em>function references</em></a>. It also permits <em>pointers-to-member-functions</em>.</p>\n<p>But <strong>does it permit references-to-member-functions</strong>?</p>\n<p>I can't seem to deduce the rules from the standard, and I've failed to make a program work with them.</p>